# Your First Steps Into Web Development

If you've ever wanted to create websites or web applications but felt intimidated by all the technical jargon, you're in the right place. This guide will walk you through setting up your computer for web development, step by step.

{% callout type="info" title="What We'll Cover" %}
By the end of this guide, you'll have everything you need to start building web applications:
- A **terminal** (command line) ready to use
- **Node.js** installed via NVM (Node Version Manager)
- A **code editor** to write your code
{% /callout %}

## Understanding the Basics

Before we dive in, let's clarify some terms:

- **Terminal / Command Line**: A text-based interface to interact with your computer. Instead of clicking on icons, you type commands.
- **Node.js**: A runtime that allows you to run JavaScript (a programming language) outside of a web browser.
- **NVM (Node Version Manager)**: A tool that lets you install and switch between different versions of Node.js easily.
- **Code Editor**: An application where you write your code, similar to Microsoft Word but for programming.

{% card title="Why NVM?" variant="feature" %}
Using NVM instead of installing Node.js directly gives you:
- Easy version switching between projects
- No permission issues on macOS and Linux
- Clean uninstalls and upgrades
- Better compatibility with different projects
{% /card %}

